      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors earlier; you are absolutely right to ask for the actual math without the distractions.\n\nThe formula for calculating the interest portion of your monthly payment is simply: **Previous Month's Balance × Annual Interest Rate ÷ 12**.\n\nThis means the interest is calculated on the *outstanding* balance at the start of the month. Since your balance hasn't changed much yet, the interest charge remains high, consuming almost your entire fixed payment. Once the balance drops significantly, the interest charge shrinks, and the remaining part of your payment finally starts aggressively reducing the principal.\n\nIn short, your payment is split into two parts: the interest (which is fixed by the formula above) and the principal reduction (which is whatever is left over). That's why the balance moves so slowly at first.",
